results in worse prognosis than Ig/BCL6.

Akasaka T(1), Ueda C, Kurata M, Akasaka H, Yamabe H, Uchiyama T, Ohno H.

Author information:
(1)First Division, Department of Internal Medicine, Faculty of Medicine, Kyoto 
University, Kyoto, Japan.

Chromosomal translocation involving the BCL6 gene affects not only 
immunoglobulin (Ig) genes but also a number of non-Ig genes as partners. The 
molecular anatomy of the BCL6 gene rearrangements in 39 cases with diffuse large 
B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) by long-distance polymerase chain reaction-based assays 
was determined. The results showed that Ig genes were affected in 21 cases; 
non-Ig genes, 15 cases; a deletion of more than a 1-kb segment, 2 cases; and a 
